# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ecmp-routing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] In computer science, **consistent hashing** is a special kind of hashing technique such that when a hash table is resized, only $n/m$ keys need to be remapped on average where n is the number of keys and m is the number of slots.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing evenly distributes cache keys across shards, even if some of the shards crash or become unavailable.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] In contrast, in most traditional hash tables, a change in the number of array slots causes nearly all keys to be remapped because the mapping between the keys and the slots is defined by a modular operation.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is used by Content Delivery Networks because it is useful for distributing requests for content from a rotating population of web servers.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Tim Berners-Lee credits consistent hashing algorithms, and Daniel Lewin as their inventor, with solving the slashdotting problem which plagued the World Wide Web in the 1990s.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] The term "consistent hashing" was introduced by David Karger *et al.* at MIT for use in distributed caching, particularly for the web.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] This academic paper from 1997 in Symposium on Theory of Computing introduced the term "consistent hashing" as a way of distributing requests among a changing population of web servers.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Each slot is then represented by a server in a distributed system or cluster.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] The addition of a server and the removal of a server (during scalability or outage) requires only $num\_keys/num\_slots$ items to be re-shuffled when the number of slots (i.e. servers) change.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] The authors mention linear hashing and its ability to handle sequential server addition and removal, while consistent hashing allows servers to be added and removed in an arbitrary order.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] The paper was later re-purposed to address technical challenge of keeping track of a file in peer-to-peer networks such as a distributed hash table.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Teradata used this technique in their distributed database, released in 1986, although they did not use this term.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Teradata still uses the concept of a hash table to fulfill exactly this purpose.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Akamai Technologies was founded in 1998 by the scientists Daniel Lewin and F.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Thomson Leighton (co-authors of the article coining "consistent hashing").
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] In Akamai's content delivery network, consistent hashing is used to balance the load within a cluster of servers, while a stable marriage algorithm is used to balance load across clusters.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing has also been used to reduce the impact of partial system failures in large web applications to provide robust caching without incurring the system-wide fallout of a failure.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is also the cornerstone of distributed hash tables (DHTs), which employ hash values to partition a keyspace across a distributed set of nodes, then construct an overlay network of connected nodes that provide efficient node retrieval by key.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique .
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] It achieves the goals of consistent hashing using the very different highest random weight (HRW) algorithm.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] However, when a server is added or removed during outage or scaling (when n changes), all the BLOBs in every server should be reassigned and moved due to rehashing, but this operation is expensive.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing was designed to avoid the problem of having to reassign every BLOB when a server is added or removed throughout the cluster.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] The central idea is to use a hash function that maps both the BLOB and servers to a unit circle, usually $2\pi$ radians.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] For example, $\zeta =\Phi \ \%\ 360$ (where $\Phi$ is hash of a BLOB or server's identifier, like IP address or UUID).
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Each BLOB is then assigned to the next server that appears on the circle in clockwise order.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] This provides an even distribution of BLOBs to servers.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] But, more importantly, if a server fails and is removed from the circle, only the BLOBs that were mapped to the failed server need to be reassigned to the next server in clockwise order.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Likewise, if a new server is added, it is added to the unit circle, and only the BLOBs mapped to that server need to be reassigned.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Importantly, when a server is added or removed, the vast majority of the BLOBs maintain their prior server assignments, and the addition of $n^{th}$ server only causes $1/n$ fraction of the BLOBs to relocate.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Although the process of moving BLOBs across cache servers in the cluster depends on the context, commonly, the newly added cache server identifies its "predecessor" and moves all the BLOBs, whose mapping belongs to this server (i.e. whose hash value is less than that of the new server), from it.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] However, in the case of web page caches, in most implementations there is no involvement of moving or copying, assuming the cached BLOB is small enough.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] When a request hits a newly added cache server, a cache miss happens and a request to the actual web server is made and the BLOB is cached locally for future requests.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] The redundant BLOBs on the previously used cache servers would be removed as per the cache eviction policies.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Let $h_{b}(x)$ and $h_{s}(x)$ be the hash functions used for the BLOB and server's unique identifier respectively.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] In practice, a binary search tree (BST) is used to dynamically maintain the ${\text{server ID}}$ within a cluster or hashring, and to find the successor or minimum within the BST, tree traversal is used.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] To avoid skewness of multiple nodes within the radian, which happen due to lack of uniform distribution of the servers within the cluster, multiple labels are used.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Those duplicate labels are called "virtual nodes" i.e. multiple labels which point to a single "real" label or server within the cluster.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] The amount of virtual nodes or duplicate labels used for a particular server within a cluster is called the "weight" of that particular server.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] A number of extensions to the basic technique are needed for effectively using consistent hashing for load balancing in practice.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] In the basic scheme above, if a server fails, all its BLOBs are reassigned to the next server in clockwise order, potentially doubling the load of that server.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] To ensure a more even redistribution of BLOBs on server failure, each server can be hashed to multiple locations on the unit circle.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] When a server fails, the BLOBs assigned to each of its replicas on the unit circle will get reassigned to a different server in clockwise order, thus redistributing the BLOBs more evenly.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Another extension concerns a situation where a single BLOB gets "hot" and is accessed a large number of times and will have to be hosted in multiple servers.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] In this situation, the BLOB may be assigned to multiple contiguous servers by traversing the unit circle in clockwise order.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] A more complex practical consideration arises when two BLOBs are hashed near each other in the unit circle and both get "hot" at the same time.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] In this case, both BLOBs will use the same set of contiguous servers in the unit circle.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] This situation can be ameliorated by each BLOB choosing a different hash function for mapping servers to the unit circle.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique, and permits fully distributed agreement on a set of k options out of a possible set of n options.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] It can in fact be shown that consistent hashing is a special case of rendezvous hashing.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] Because of its simplicity and generality, rendezvous hashing is now being used in place of Consistent Hashing in many applications.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] If key values will always increase monotonically, an alternative approach using a hash table with monotonic keys may be more suitable than consistent hashing.
[src:ecmp-routing/consistent-hashing] The $O(K/N)$ is an average cost for redistribution of keys and the $O(\log N)$ complexity for consistent hashing comes from the fact that a binary search among nodes angles is required to find the next node on the ring.
[src:ecmp-routing/equal-cost-multi-path-routing] RFC 2992 analyzed one particular multipath routing strategy involving the assignment of flows through hashing flow-related data in the packet header.
[src:ecmp-routing/equal-cost-multi-path-routing] This solution is designed to avoid these problems by sending all packets from any particular network flow through the same path while balancing multiple flows over multiple paths in general.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] A **forwarding information base** (**FIB**), also known as a **forwarding table** or **MAC** (**address**) **table**, is most commonly used in network bridging, routing, and similar functions to find the proper output network interface controller to which the input interface should forward a packet.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] It is a dynamic table that maps MAC addresses to ports.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] It is the essential mechanism that separates network switches from Ethernet hubs.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] Content-addressable memory (CAM) is typically used to efficiently implement the FIB, thus it is sometimes called a **CAM table**.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] At the data link layer, a FIB is most notably used to facilitate Ethernet bridging based on MAC addresses.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] Other data-link-layer technologies using FIBs include Frame Relay, Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS).
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] The role of an Ethernet switch is to forward Ethernet frames from one port to another.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] The presence of a FIB is one attribute that separates a switch from a hub.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] Without a functional FIB, all frames received by a network switch would be echoed back out to all other ports, much like an Ethernet hub.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] Switches learn the port on which they first saw a particular source address and associate that port with that address.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] When the bridge subsequently receives a frame with a destination address in its FIB, it sends the frame out the port stored in the FIB entry.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] The FIB is a memory construct used by Ethernet switch to map a station's MAC address to the switch port the station is connected to.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] This allows switches to facilitate communications between connected stations at high speed.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] While the exact mechanics of a forwarding table is implementation-specific, the general model for Frame Relay is that switches have statically defined forwarding tables, one per interface.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] When a frame with a given data link connection identifier (DLCI) is received on one interface, the table associated with that interface gives the outgoing interface, and the new DLCI to insert into the frame's address field.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] ATM switches have link-level forwarding tables much like those used in Frame Relay.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] Rather than a DLCI, however, interfaces have forwarding tables that specify the outgoing interface by *virtual path identifier* (VPI) and *virtual circuit identifier* (VCI).
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] These tables may be configured statically, or they can be distributed by the Private Network-to-Network Interface (PNNI) protocol.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] When PNNI is in use, the ATM switches at the edges of the network map one of the standard ATM end-to-end identifiers, such as an NSAP address, to the next-hop VPI/VCI.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] MPLS has many similarities, at the forwarding level, to ATM.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] The label edge routers at the edges of an MPLS cloud map between the end-to-end identifier, such as an IP address, and a link-local label.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] At each MPLS hop, there is a forwarding table that tells the label-switched router which outgoing interface is to receive the MPLS packet, and what label to use when sending the packet out that interface.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] Network layer addresses, such as IP addresses, are used on different types of media and can be handled similarly in all cases.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] FIBs are optimized for fast lookup of destination addresses and can improve performance of forwarding compared to using the routing information base (RIB) directly.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] The RIB is optimized for efficient updating by routing protocols and other control plane methods, and contain the full set of routes learned by the router.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] Earlier implementations cached only a subset of the routes most frequently used in actual forwarding, and this worked reasonably well for enterprises where there is a meaningful most-frequently-used subset.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] Routers used for accessing the entire Internet, however, experienced severe performance degradation in refreshing routes cached in a small FIB, and various implementations moved to having FIBs in one-to-one correspondence with the RIB.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] FIBs can also play a role in an Internet best current practice (BCP) of ingress filtering.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] While the IETF document BCP 38 on ingress filtering does not specify a method of implementing source address filtering, some router vendors have implemented a mechanism that employs reverse-path forwarding lookups in the router's tables to perform this check.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] This is often implemented as a lookup in the FIB of the *source* address of the packet.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] If the interface has no route to the source address, the packet is assumed to be part of a denial of service attack, using a spoofed source address, and the router discards the packet.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] When the router is multihomed, ingress filtering becomes more complex.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] There are perfectly reasonable operational scenarios in which a packet could arrive on one interface, but that specific interface might not have a route to the source address.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] For the routers near the edge of the Internet, packet filters can provide a simpler and more effective solution than methods that employ routing information lookup, though this approach can be challenging when managing routers that are reconfigured often.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] Ingress filtering for multihomed routers will accept the packet if there is a route back to its source address from *any* interface on the router.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] For this type of filtering, the router may also maintain an *adjacency table*, also organized for fast lookup, that keeps track of the router interface addresses that are on all directly connected routers.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] Differentiated services provides an additional method to select outgoing interfaces, based on a field that indicates the forwarding priority of the packet, as well as the preference of the packet to be dropped in the presence of congestion.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] Routers that support differentiated service not only have to look up the output interface for the destination address, but need to send the packet to the interface that best matches the differentiated services requirements.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] In other words, as well as matching the destination address, the FIB has to match differentiated services code points (DSCP).
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] Specific router implementations may, when a destination address or other FIB criterion is matched, specify another action to be done before forwarding (e.g., accounting or encryption), or apply an access control list that may cause the packet to be dropped.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] CAM tables can be targeted for setting up a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] A threat agent which has control of a device connected to an Ethernet switch can use MAC flooding to attack the switch's CAM table.
[src:ecmp-routing/forwarding-information-base] If the table fills up, other traffic is treated as broadcast, unknown-unicast and multicast traffic and is forwarded to all ports making it available to the attacker.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] Networks are separated from each other by specialized hosts, called gateways or routers with specialized software support optimized for routing.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] **IP forwarding** algorithms in most routing software determine a route through a shortest path algorithm.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] In routers, packets arriving at an interface are examined for source and destination addressing and queued to the appropriate outgoing interface according to their destination address and a set of rules and performance metrics.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] Rules are encoded in a routing table that contains entries for all interfaces and their connected networks.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] If no rule satisfies the requirements for a network packet, it is forwarded to a default route.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] Routing tables are maintained either manually by a network administrator, or updated dynamically by a routing protocol.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] A routing protocol specifies how routers communicate and share information about the topology of the network, and the capabilities of each routing node.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] Different protocols are often used for different topologies or different application areas.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] For example, the Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) protocol is generally used within an enterprise and the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) is used on a global scale.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] BGP is the de facto standard for worldwide Internet routing.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] Routing protocols may be broadly distinguished by their realm of operation in terms of network scope.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] Interior gateway protocols are used for routing within autonomous systems, while exterior gateway protocols route traffic between them.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] The former group is exemplified by the Routing Information Protocol (RIP) and Open Shortest Path First (OSPF), while the Exterior Gateway Protocol (EGP) and the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) are examples of the exterior type.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] BGP is the dominant route distribution protocol used on the Internet.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] The IP forwarding algorithm is a specific implementation of routing for IP networks.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] In order to achieve a successful transfer of data, the algorithm uses a routing table to select a next-hop router as the next destination for a datagram.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] When multiple route table entries match, the entry with the longest subnet mask is chosen as it is the most specific one.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] If there are multiple routes with the same subnet mask, the route with the lowest metric is used.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] If there are multiple default routes, the metric is also used to determine which to use.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] If there are multiple routes with the same subnet mask and metric, the system may use equal-cost multi-path routing as a forwarding strategy.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] When no route is available, an ICMP error message is sent to the originator of the packet, to inform that host that the packet could not be delivered.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] To avoid unnecessary retransmission to avoid network congestion, the sending host should either stop transmitting or choose another address or route.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] The host has several network interfaces.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] *eth0* is the interface name of the network interface card representing an Ethernet port.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] *ppp0* is a PPPoE interface, which is configured as the default route in this example.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] A default route is recognized by the destination *0.0.0.0* and the flag *G*.
[src:ecmp-routing/ip-routing] A network router is identified by the network mask *255.255.255.255* and the flag *H*.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:ecmp-routing/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] In computer networking, a **routing table**, or **routing information base** (**RIB**), is a data table stored in a router or a network host that lists the routes to particular network destinations, and in some cases, metrics (distances) associated with those routes.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] The routing table contains information about the topology of the network immediately around it.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] The construction of routing tables is the primary goal of routing protocols.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] Static routes are entries that are fixed, rather than resulting from routing protocols and network topology discovery procedures.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] A routing table is analogous to a distribution map in package delivery.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] Whenever a node needs to send data to another node on a network, it must first know *where* to send it.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] If the node cannot directly connect to the destination node, it has to send it via other nodes along a route to the destination node.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] Each node needs to keep track of which way to deliver various packages of data, and for this, it uses a routing table.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] A routing table is a database that keeps track of paths, like a map, and uses these to determine which way to forward traffic.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] A routing table is a data file in RAM that is used to store route information about directly connected and remote networks.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] Nodes can also share the contents of their routing table with other nodes.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] The primary function of a router is to forward a packet toward its destination network, which is the destination IP address of the packet.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] To do this, a router needs to search the routing information stored in its routing table.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] The routing table contains network/next hop associations.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] These associations tell a router that a particular destination can be optimally reached by sending the packet to a specific router that represents the next hop on the way to the final destination.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] The next hop association can also be the outgoing or exit interface to the final destination.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] With hop-by-hop routing, each routing table lists, for all reachable destinations, the address of the next device along the path to that destination: the next hop.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] Assuming that the routing tables are consistent, the simple algorithm of relaying packets to their destination's next hop thus suffices to deliver data anywhere in a network.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] Hop-by-hop is the fundamental characteristic of the IP Internet layer and the OSI Network Layer.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] When a router interface is configured with an IP address and subnet mask, the interface becomes a host on that attached network.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] A directly connected network is a network that is directly attached to one of the router interfaces.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] The network address and subnet mask of the interface, along with the interface type and number, are entered into the routing table as a directly connected network.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] A remote network is a network that can only be reached by sending the packet to another router.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] Routing table entries to remote networks may be either dynamic or static.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] Dynamic routes are routes to remote networks that were learned automatically by the router through a dynamic routing protocol.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] Static routes are routes that a network administrator manually configured.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] Routing tables are also a key aspect of certain security operations, such as unicast reverse path forwarding (uRPF).
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] In this technique, which has several variants, the router also looks up, in the routing table, the *source address* of the packet.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] If there exists no route back to the source address, the packet is assumed to be malformed or involved in a network attack and is dropped.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] The need to record routes to large numbers of devices using limited storage space represents a major challenge in routing table construction.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] On the Internet, the currently dominant address aggregation technology is a bitwise prefix matching scheme called Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR).
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] Supernetworks can also be used to help control routing table size.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] *metric*: The routing metric of the path through which the packet is to be sent.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] The route will go in the direction of the gateway with the lowest metric.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] *interface*: Such as eth0 for the first Ethernet card, eth1 for the second Ethernet card, etc.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] Routing tables are generally not used directly for packet forwarding in modern router architectures; instead, they are used to generate the information for a simpler forwarding table.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] This forwarding table contains only the routes that are chosen by the routing algorithm as preferred routes for packet forwarding.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] It is often in a compressed or pre-compiled format that is optimized for hardware storage and lookup.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] This router architecture separates the control plane function of the routing table from the forwarding plane function of the forwarding table.
[src:ecmp-routing/routing-table] This separation of control and forwarding provides uninterrupted high-performance forwarding.
